  "title": "Education Experiments",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "de023c0697388423",
      "text": "Context; Experiment; Findings; Conclusions"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5a987f1af64e41ce",
      "text": "# Context\nWhen I ([[Kerry Turner]]) first decided to pass my systems know-how on to children I started by asking my old colleagues in consulting whether they had done the same for their children."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e7e2f4140b6676d9",
      "text": "Some of them told me they hadn't because it wasn't on the curriculum and kids get marked down for using techniques not on the curriculum even though they are superior!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3c9d1360088dfc90",
      "text": "Others told me they were too busy at work to do that. They were working to pay for their kids education. When I asked them \"what about the other kids?\" They told me that was not their responsibility. So I explained how inequality would create big problems for their children and that if they wanted a better world for their kids they should join me in teaching all kids what we know. They did not seem to want to understand!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7756ef3356b6d3b6",
      "text": "They didn't understand either that applying ST to optimise a part (called a business) would not optimise the whole. It would actually create massive problems for all children. None of them seemed to care. After all they all had debts to pay!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d785ab1806b3fd9f",
      "text": "So I was on  my own! Nothing new there!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "323f2d33d7460c00",
      "text": "# Experiments"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "82afe4577772fae5",
      "text": "1. **Change the UK Education System** (top down). This was based on an assumption that turned out to be false: That the powers that be would want the system to be improved! Once again I turned out to be wrong. \nI thought that the best way in would be through my subject \"Maths\" and I contacted the committee that sets the Maths curriculum. I thought I was in luck as the Chair was Prof of Math and Systems @ Cambridge university.\nAt first he didn't respond but I persisted. He agreed with me but said it was impossible as he couldn't find teachers to teach basic maths!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0564fee3da5f2329",
      "text": "2. I then reached out to the Exam Boards. Again I thought I'd got lucky. The **Oxford & Cambridge Exam Board** had just introduced an A level in Critical Thinking. I talked to them about the syllabus as it was more about critiquing than thinking. They didn't ant to change it. to get rid of me they put me on a mailing list of teachers teaching Crit thinking. Multiple times I offered to teach them ST for free. Not one teacher took me up on my offer!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5ff5e21669f85677",
      "text": "3. I then thought that teachers must do ongoing prof dev. They do! And many businesses offer this training. I contacted the biggest = **Osiris Education**. At the first in-person meeting I threatened to leave as they were disrespecting my (and more importantly my dad's) time. My dad was patiently waiting outside in the car he had driven me over in....\nThis stopped them playing games and they got interested. They offered me a \"deal\". I would give their board a weekend workshop to use it on their own strategy. In return they would give me access to their teachers and let me run a PD course for teachers.\nThe workshop went well but the owner refused to keep his side of the bargain. Why? He told me that it had been hard work....too hard for teachers on a jolly from work. That he had competitors who offered an equally good day off work - nice food, surroundings, a it of learning but not too much. I was too much. ST is too much!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "53171ffdc7943f41",
      "text": "4. This made me give up on teachers for a while. Instead I thought well kids do other stuff than school and a lot of them will be getting interested in sport ad the London Olympics was coming up. I went to **Sports Coaching UK** - the same thing happened. I led a board workshop. They loved it. They said their coaches were too stupid to learn and pass this on.\nI didn't do anything for a long time after that!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e6c1a8269f6eea00",
      "text": "5. I decided to seek help and enroll on a **PhD** in the **Centre for Systems Studies at the University of Hull** to get some cover to get into schools. A university email address and the promise of academic research started to open a few doors for me. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b86847e2ba6ecdd3",
      "text": "6. Becoming a **STEM Ambassador** gave me **DBS clearance** and again more security."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3c45e6ab8687dcd5",
      "text": "7. The **OR Society** supported me by covering my expenses and giving me a supported place to present my project at the annual conference."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2073ce6eb7a4ed91",
      "text": "8. I did a number of experiments at **Chapeltown Academy**, Sheffield, where my niece had been in the 6th form. \n(a) I offered a course in *Business Thinking* and made it easy to participate (free, in school hours etc). At the first session 10 students turned up. At the second, there were only 3. I asked the 7 why they had given up and they told me that it was difficult and they weren't going to get a qualification that would help them to get into university! By the third session I had only one boy who stuck with it through thick and thin (including getting laughed at by his peers in the common room when he was sitting talking to me!) I asked him why he had continued with me when all his pals had quit. He told me that he could see how he could use this everywhere and that he was quitting chemistry A level to give himself time to develop his skill. That one boy gave me the hope to carry on. \n(b) I also did sessions with the *geography* students. We explored climate change as a system and discovered the options humanity faces. When asked how they felt about the future scenarios that emerged from their model one boy said he had a different solution. He told us that we could all get on a space ship and escape to another planet. So I asked him what would happen to the new planet if nobody changed their mindset on the journey and he almost shouted that the same thing would happen to that planet. I asked what should we do then? And he said we have to change our mindset and our behavior. This is not dissimilar to [[Do It Naturally]].I wonder if that boy changed *his* mindset and behavior?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f69d9268a6f63688",
      "text": "9. Through Hull University (and the OR Society) I met systems lecturer, Giles Hindle. He told me that his children were **unschool**ed. He let them do what they want. I said what if they do nothing? He said they'll experience the consequences. He waits for them to ask him questions then he asks them how they would answer the question! His daughter is into horses and so that is what she does. I guess that is the same as we learnt from age 0 to school!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "96823e95e6f86530",
      "text": "10. As a result of a workshop I gave to **SciO** I got help from a number of people including Bill Tate and Steve Whitla. Bill introduced me to Larry Sullivan of the **COINS Foundation** and that resulted in me helping with their programme with *SEND* children. Steve Whitla introduced me to the headteacher at the school his kids attended."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "779ed06d2a6132bb",
      "text": "11. Tina Farr is the head of **St Ebbe's Primary school, Oxford** [https://st-ebbes.oxon.sch.uk/ link] I ran a workshop for her SLT. she decided to use it not to teach the curriculum but to deal with situations as they arose in the school. She told me a story of 2 boys fighting on the playground. She asked them what had happened and why. One boy explained the history and the other agreed. She asked what would be the consequences if this continued and they explained that people would get hurt and others would be disturbed. She asked what should happen next and they said they should be punished! They suggested they wanted to be punished by missing their break the next day as they had spoiled this break for the others. Because they had been so fair she offered them the opportunity to play a game of their choice while they were locked inside! This gives me *Hope*!!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "14262b0b9066eb07",
      "text": "12. I won a scholarship to do the Capra Course and met a lady who worked at **Brockwood Park school** (the Krishnamurthi school in the UK [https://brockwood.org.uk/ link])). I gave a workshop there. Krishnamurthi actually said that kids should be allowed to discover their talent...their unique gifts to bring to the whole. See [[Krishnamurthi on Education]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0e2b5dd86958177e",
      "text": "13. I had a go at getting the UK network of **Brownies/Guides and scouts** to engage. I envisaged a systems thinking badge for the brownies! The central leadership were not interested so I reached out to the Wombwell Brownie pack I had participated in when a child. I ran a session with the dominoes for kids aged 4-13. It went very well."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d05307c9e23cf8a3",
      "text": "14. Giles Hindle's partner introduced me to the Hull **Home Education** Group. I ran a number of workshops at the university. I learned that it can be difficult having mixed ages/abilities. The young 10 year old got it first and then helped me to teach the 16 year olds and their parents! See [[The Modern Trivium]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e0500e28e2050728",
      "text": "15. I applied for and won a grant from the **[[Ferens Education Trust]]** to support **Hull & East Yorkshire Children's University** [https://www.hullchildrensuniversity.com/ link] to build a systems thinking experience with local company, Rix. We ran the prototype at Victory Homes but Covid stopped play. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7d1d4e15138a5130",
      "text": "16. I went to MIT, Boston to meet Peter Senge for the third time. He gave me a supported place on his **Compassionate Systems Programme** run by the Center for Systems Awareness [https://systemsawareness.org/program/intro-to-compassionate-systems-leadership-juneb2022/ link]. It is very expensive to attend. It is aimed at the elite private schools. What does that tell us?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "afef29386f789e80",
      "text": "17. I came across Vishnu Agnihotri online. He runs **Genwise India** - an out of school program for gifted children. I went to India and worked with the kids for a week. See [[Passage to India]].One of the children was exceptionally gifted."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "fae25aa11520fe5d",
      "text": "18. In 2020 I went to **Colombia** to speak at a conference titled \"Education for the 21st Century\". I ran workshops at two schools: [https://www.kalapa.com.co/ Kalapa] and [https://gimnasiomoderno.edu.co/ Gimnasio Moderno] a central Bogota private international boys school. What a contrast!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "92b06fa93d19e98b",
      "text": "19. In 2021 I ran a summer program for kids at the **Oregon City High School** in the USA. It was my first attempt at delivering what I called a [[See the Systems]] experience. The kids (around 160 14-15 year olds) and teachers were in-person and I was online. I was literally carried around the school on a computer screen! See [[OCHS Bridge SYSTEMS]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f7341d7fb32b7d69",
      "text": "20. In 2022 I ran a spring program for the **San Francisco Friends School** at the [https://www.woolman.org/mission Woolman Quaker Centre] near Nevada City in the Sierra Nevada, California. It was the same format as OCHS but with younger children (12 year olds.) From these two programs I noticed that the teachers did not support the children in implementing their projects (experiments) after the event."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b84774d19f183b91",
      "text": "21. [[Relocalize Creativity]] is about empowering communities with the tools they need to be high performing systems. [[Chris Casillas]] reached out to us to support him in transforming his neighborhood in Superior, AZ, USA. **Regenerate Sonora** is the result. Chris realizes that for his initiative to be long term viable he needs to bring on the next generation of community activists. This is what I needed to learn. \nThis could also be an opportunity to do an experiment with the [[Systemic Entrepreneurship course]] I co-created with Jamie Keeling."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2171ea6a38a1c6e0",
      "text": "22. The **[[Youth Sports Trust]]** is a new project with a lot of potential. The YST want me to teach them what they need to reach the \"system out there\". Their aim is to change the same system I am...there is synergy and potential."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "0350da6b4e055ff3",
      "text": "23. I have been helping a group of Deans from the **University of Leeds** on their journey to discover causal loop diagrams (communal loop drawings). My hope is that this will \"filter down\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f39fb8ab022c6cca",
      "text": "24. **[[Banana Mountain]]** is a community school in Orgiva, Spain. We ran a workshop (see [[Banana Mountain Workshop]] on 2/3 November 2023 with the students, staff and parents."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "424908c04d5a8254",
      "text": "25. **Horses** are good for people. They teach us responsibility and respect. Winston Churchill said \"there is nothing so good for the inside of a man as the outisde of a horse\". I would modify it and say *\"there is nothing so good for the wholeness of a human being as the wholeness of a horse\"*. See [[Riding Dynamics]]. I have learned so much from **[[Willy Sidorak]]**. He taught me that hen we (or should I say \"I\"?)  try to prevent failure we prevent learning. He taught me that learning through experiments with horses can be life changing. Willy would die for learning. He has devoted his life to a big experiment to explore how to create and maintain a horse on full power from conception to grave. How can we help Willy to create a *European Centre of Excellence for Ethical Horsemanship*?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "83f50a6c4d6b191a",
      "text": "26. **Parents** are vitally important. My dad could not really read or write. He left school at 13 yrs old and went as an apprentice to my grandfather who was a master joiner. My dad taught me a lot of things. He said that if I wanted to learn how to do something I should find someone I admire and watch them closely. He said that those who are naturally talented rarely know what it is they are doing. He said observe and ask questions but remember that they are not you. You will have to try it for yourself and find your own way. Trial and error. "
    },
